Relationships between \(\arg(z)\) and \(\arg(z^{\bullet})\), \(\left|z\right|\) and \(\left|z^{\bullet}\right|\)

Let the points \(P\) and \(P^{\bullet}\) represent the complex numbers \(z=x+\mathrm{i}y\) and \(z^{\bullet}=x-\mathrm{i}y\), \(x\), \(y\in\mathbb{R}\) respectively on an Argand diagram.

Observe that \(P\) and \(P^{\bullet}\) are reflections of each other about the real axis.

From the diagram, it is clear that

\[\left|z^{\bullet}\right|=\left|z\right|\text{ and }\arg(z^{\bullet})=-\arg(z)\.\]

Also,

\[zz^{\bullet}=x^{2}+y^{2}=\left|z\right|^{2}.\]

In polar form,

if \(z=r\mathbf{c}^{\mathrm{i}\theta}\), then \(z^{\bullet}=r\mathbf{c}^{-\mathrm{i}\theta}\).

